[[File:Sourdoughbreadcrumb.jpg|thumb|Sourdough bread pores]]
'''Pores''' are the air pockets found in [[Leavening agent|leavened]] bread, where [[carbon dioxide]] from the [[Fermentation (food)|fermentation process]] creates a network of primarily interconnected void structures.<ref name="sciencedirect">{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0733521011000956 |title=It’s a maze: The pore structure of bread crumbs |accessdate=2014-12-29|doi=10.1016/j.jcs.2011.05.004|volume=54|journal=Journal of Cereal Science|pages=203–210}}</ref><ref name="insidefood">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidefood.eu/INSIDEFOOD_WEB/UK/WORD/proceedings/042P.pdf |title=From dough to bread: the setting up of a heterogeneous cellular structure|publisher=insidefood.eu|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref> The degree to which pores form are a major determiner in the texture ("crumb") of the bread.<ref name="kocaeli">{{cite web|url=http://akademikpersonel.kocaeli.edu.tr/ozge.ozkoc/sci/ozge.ozkoc30.03.2010_16.31.41sci.pdf |title=Porous media characterization of breads baked using novel heating modes |publisher=akademikpersonel.kocaeli.edu.tr|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref><ref name="uwa">{{cite web|url=http://www.ioa.uwa.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/2120186/5-shuo-for-web.pdf |title=Controlling quality and texture through digitizing breads and doughs |publisher=ioa.uwa.edu.au|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref> Pore size varies between varieties of bread. [[Sourdough bread]] is a variety with larger pores. [[Rye bread]] has smaller pores and a denser crumb.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Understanding Food: Principles and Preparation|author=Brown, A.|date=2007|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=9780495107453|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=edPzm5KSMmYC|page=397|accessdate=2014-12-29}}</ref> [[File:Kommissbrot.jpg|thumb|Rye bread pores]]
